#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:1
msgid "Controlling panics with `std::panic`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.9](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.9-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:5
msgid ""
"There is a `std::panic` module, which includes methods for halting the "
"unwinding process started by a panic:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:12
msgid "\"hello!\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:17
msgid "\"oh no!\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:22
msgid ""
"In general, Rust distinguishes between two ways that an operation can fail:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:24
msgid "Due to an _expected problem_, like a file not being found."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:25
msgid ""
"Due to an _unexpected problem_, like an index being out of bounds for an "
"array."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:27
msgid ""
"Expected problems usually arise from conditions that are outside of your "
"control; robust code should be prepared for anything its environment might "
"throw at it. In Rust, expected problems are handled via [the `Result` type]"
"(http://doc.rust-lang.org/std/result/index.html), which allows a function to "
"return information about the problem to its caller, which can then handle "
"the error in a fine-grained way."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:35
msgid ""
"Unexpected problems are _bugs_: they arise due to a contract or assertion "
"being violated. Since they are unexpected, it doesn't make sense to handle "
"them in a fine-grained way. Instead, Rust employs a \"fail fast\" approach "
"by _panicking_, which by default unwinds the stack (running destructors but "
"no other code) of the thread which discovered the error. Other threads "
"continue running, but will discover the panic any time they try to "
"communicate with the panicked thread (whether through channels or shared "
"memory). Panics thus abort execution up to some \"isolation boundary\", with "
"code on the other side of the boundary still able to run, and perhaps to "
"\"recover\" from the panic in some very coarse-grained way. A server, for "
"example, does not necessarily need to go down just because of an assertion "
"failure in one of its threads."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:47
msgid ""
"It's also worth noting that programs may choose to _abort_ instead of "
"unwind, and so catching panics may not work. If your code relies on "
"`catch_unwind`, you should add this to your Cargo.toml:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:51
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[profile.debug]\n"
"panic = \"unwind\"\n"
"\n"
"[profile.release]\n"
"panic = \"unwind\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:59
msgid ""
"If any of your users choose to abort, they'll get a compile-time failure."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:61
msgid ""
"The `catch_unwind` API offers a way to introduce new isolation boundaries "
"_within a thread_. There are a couple of key motivating examples:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:64
msgid "Embedding Rust in other languages"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:65
msgid "Abstractions that manage threads"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:66
msgid ""
"Test frameworks, because tests may panic and you don't want that to kill the "
"test runner"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:68
msgid ""
"For the first case, unwinding across a language boundary is undefined "
"behavior, and often leads to segfaults in practice. Allowing panics to be "
"caught means that you can safely expose Rust code via a C API, and translate "
"unwinding into an error on the C side."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:73
msgid ""
"For the second case, consider a threadpool library. If a thread in the pool "
"panics, you generally don't want to kill the thread itself, but rather catch "
"the panic and communicate it to the client of the pool. The `catch_unwind` "
"API is paired with `resume_unwind`, which can then be used to restart the "
"panicking process on the client of the pool, where it belongs."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/controlling-panics-with-std-panic.md:79
msgid ""
"In both cases, you're introducing a new isolation boundary within a thread, "
"and then translating the panic into some other form of error elsewhere."
msgstr ""
